The question asks for the square of the derivative of the function \(f(x)=\sin(\cos(\tan(x)))\), which we can find using the chain rule:

\begin{align*}
f'(x) &= \cos(\cos(\tan(x)))\cdot(-\sin(\tan(x)))\cdot\sec^2(x) \\
&= -\cos(\cos(\tan(x)))\cdot\sin(\tan(x))\cdot\frac{1}{\cos^2(x)} \\
&= -\frac{\cos(\cos(\tan(x)))\cdot\sin(\tan(x))}{\cos^2(x)} \\
\end{align*}

Squaring this expression, we get:

\begin{align*}
f'(x)^2 &= \frac{\cos^2(\cos(\tan(x)))\cdot\sin^2(\tan(x))}{\cos^4(x)} \\
&= \frac{\sin^2(\tan(x))}{\cos^4(x)}\cdot\cos^2(\cos(\tan(x))) \\
&= \frac{\sin^2(\tan(x))}{\cos^4(x)}\cdot\biggl(1-\sin^2(\cos(\tan(x)))\biggr) \\
&= \frac{\sin^2(\tan(x))\cdot\bigl(1-\sin^2(\cos(\tan(x)))\bigr)}{\cos^4(x)}
\end{align*}

Therefore, the answer is:

\[f'(x)^2=\frac{\sin^2(\tan(x))\cdot\bigl(1-\sin^2(\cos(\tan(x)))\bigr)}{\cos^4(x)}\]

